                <cell>mole (mol)</cell>
            </row>

            <row>
                <cell header="yes">Luminous intensity</cell>
                <cell>candela (cd)</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </table>

    <p>
        The column on the left is the physical quantity and the column on the right is the corresponding base unit with the symbol of the base unit included in parentheses.
        Refer to the table above to see each pairing together.
        The base unit for length is the meter.
        The base unit for mass is the kilogram.
        The base unit for time is a second.
        The base unit for temperature is the kelvin.
        And the base unit for the amount of a substance is the mole.
        Notice that kilogram, the base unit for mass, is the only base unit that includes a prefix, kilo.
        You may also notice other physical quantities like area, volume, and density are not included in this list.
        That is because they are derived units and we will cover those later.
    </p>

    <insight>
        <title>SI System - Syst√®me International</title>

        <p>
            Agreed upon by scientists and utilizes the metric system with standards
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    All units in the SI system are related to the standard unit by a power of 10.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    The power of 10 is indicated by a prefix.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    It is usually best to measure a property in a unit close to the size of the property.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
